total_energy_consumption,scope_2_emissions_tco2e,2,forbid_reverse,2,"Scope 2 emissions are indirectly generated by the purchased electricity, heat, cooling, or steam that the company consumes. Luo and Tang (2014) examined the relationship between carbon emissions and shareholder wealth, showing that, unlike Scope 1, Scope 2 emissions are not negatively correlated with abnormal returns. Choi et al. (2021) produced evidence that the negative association between carbon emissions and firm value only applies to Scope 1 emissions because those are the ones that investors use to estimate a company's potential liabilities.",735c8d3e-d9bf-46cc-9420-0cc62447afb7; cd2205e2-02b5-49b1-a547-3e9f6f80295a,yes,"auto-approved: tier 2 structural/temporal/impossibility; [audit:E] yes/high/paper_verified=yes: Paper cd2205e2 explicitly defines Scope 2 as 'indirectly generated by the purchased electricity, heat, cooling, or steam that the company consumes,' establishing an unambiguous structural/definitional link from energy consumption to Scope 2 emissions; paper 735c8d3e corroborates this framing; tier 2 structural claim with two supporting papers."
