roa_eat,scope_1_emissions_tco2e,3,review,1,"The analysis of the impact of control variables shows that firm size, return on assets (ROA), proportion of tangible assets, cash flow ratio, listing age, and book-to-market ratio have a significant positive effect on carbon emission reduction performance. Firms with a high ROA often indicates that a firm has more efficient overall operation and management, and this capability can be extended to the field of environmental management, indirectly improving emission reduction performance.",36c08073-8f0e-405a-89b7-1df36c24f412,yes,"[audit:E] modify/medium/paper_verified=yes: Paper 36c08073 is verified and confirms 'return on assets (ROA) have a significant positive effect on carbon emission reduction performance,' meaning higher ROA leads to better emission reduction (lower emissions); the direction (ROA → emissions) is correctly identified as a reverse channel, but the effect sign means higher ROA → lower scope_1_emissions_tco2e, not higher.; MOD: Correct the effect sign: higher ROA → lower scope_1_emissions_tco2e (negative direction); note this is a control variable finding from a single paper; flag as a potential confounding/reverse-causality channel rather than a primary causal constraint; useful for causal discovery as a forbidden-reverse candidate for the primary scope_1 → roa direction."
scope_1_emissions_tco2e,market_value_equity,3,review,1,"Matsumura et al. (2014), using a sample of S&P 500 firms during 2006-2008, found that firm value decreased $212,000 for every additional ton of carbon emission. Griffin et al. (2017) conducted an event study on investor reactions to carbon emissions disclosure in US firms. They found that stock prices are negatively associated with carbon emissions levels, implying a market penalty of $79 per ton emitted yearly.",2a14b689-090f-4c53-b3c4-bcd14ac3a69c; bd8d8af6-2859-4844-a069-31a9f366e947,yes,"[audit:E] yes/high/paper_verified=partial: Paper 2a14b689 cites Matsumura et al. (2014) finding firm value decreased $212,000 per additional ton of carbon emission in S&P 500 firms, and Griffin et al. (2017) finding stock prices negatively associated with emissions at $79/ton; paper bd8d8af6 confirms negative correlation between carbon emissions and market-to-book value in GCC firms; direction and sign are consistent."
scope_1_emissions_tco2e,roa_eat,3,review,1,King and Lenox (2002): Lower emissions (in t) are significantly associated with higher financial performance (in t+1). Significant and positive relationship of waste prevention with ROA and Tobin's q. Hart and Ahuja (1996): Pollution prevention activities have a positive influence on financial performance within 1-2 years. ROE takes longer to be affected. Russo and Fouts (1997): Positive and significant impact of environmental performance on ROA.,b52a324f-b7a8-4def-8442-c6462110aa2a; d9752059-5c45-4ca9-abb0-d9e936d03764,yes,"[audit:E] modify/medium/paper_verified=partial: Paper b52a324f cites King & Lenox (2002), Hart & Ahuja (1996), and Russo & Fouts (1997) as secondary evidence for a negative relationship between emissions and ROA; however, these are secondary citations within a review paper, and the primary studies are not directly retrieved; the direction (lower emissions → higher ROA) is consistent with the emission_reduction_policy_score → roa_eat constraint which is better supported.; MOD: Retain with lower confidence; note that primary evidence comes from the emission_reduction_policy_score → roa_eat constraint (papers 28376774, 30ecac5c, 9f0ca1d1) which is better supported; this constraint is redundant with that one and relies on secondary citations; if retained, flag as corroborating evidence only."
